# Polyptic — example environment.
#
# Copy to `deploy/.env` and edit. Every value below has a built-in default (shown),
# so an empty/absent .env runs the normal dev loop. Uncomment a line only to override.
#
#   cp deploy/.env.example deploy/.env
#
# These are read by the SERVER (and, where noted, the AGENT). See docs/DEV.md →
# "Configuration" for the full list, and "Phase 2b — Enrollment & approval" for the token.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Enrollment (Phase 2b)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# POLYPTIC_BOOTSTRAP_TOKEN — the shared enrollment secret.
#   UNSET (default) → OPEN MODE: every agent is auto-registered AND auto-approved,
#     exactly like Phase 2a. The server logs a prominent WARNING at boot. Dev-only;
#     never run a real deployment open.
#   SET → GATED MODE: a new agent must present this token on first contact and then
#     shows up PENDING until an operator approves it in the Admin UI. Set the SAME
#     value on each agent (its own POLYPTIC_BOOTSTRAP_TOKEN) so it can enroll.
#   The server stores only sha256(credential) per machine; the agent persists the raw
#   credential at ${POLYPTIC_STATE_DIR or ~/.polyptic}/credential-<machineId>.
# POLYPTIC_BOOTSTRAP_TOKEN=change-me-to-a-long-random-secret

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# mTLS agent identity (POL-25 / D69) — the transport layer on top of the credential
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# AGENT_MTLS_PORT — set to enable a SECOND, TLS-terminating listener serving only the
#   /agent channel. Enrolment then issues each machine a durable client certificate
#   (signed by the deployment's own CA, persisted in the store; the agent's private key
#   never leaves the box — only a CSR does) and every reconnect dials wss:// on this
#   port, where a wrong/absent/expired cert FAILS THE TLS HANDSHAKE — rejected before
#   any app code. Requires Bun ≥ 1.3: the server self-tests its own listener at boot
#   (no-cert + rogue-CA dials must fail) and EXITS if the runtime cannot verify certs.
#   The agent persists its bundle at ${POLYPTIC_STATE_DIR or ~/.polyptic}/mtls-<machineId>.json.
# AGENT_MTLS_PORT=8443

# AGENT_MTLS_REQUIRE — set to 1 once the fleet holds certs: the plain /agent channel
#   then only authenticates + issues bundles and never admits a live session. Leave
#   unset while rolling out so uncertified agents keep working while they upgrade.
# AGENT_MTLS_REQUIRE=1

# AGENT_MTLS_ADVERTISE_PORT — the port boxes should DIAL when it differs from the bind
#   AGENT_MTLS_PORT (POL-143). On Kubernetes the listener binds 8443 in the pod but is
#   reached through a NodePort (e.g. 30843); advertise the reachable one — agents reuse
#   the host they already know on this port. Unset → advertise AGENT_MTLS_PORT. A full
#   AGENT_MTLS_PUBLIC_URL below still overrides both.
# AGENT_MTLS_ADVERTISE_PORT=30843

# AGENT_MTLS_PUBLIC_URL — full wss:// URL agents should dial when the mTLS listener is
#   not "same host as the server URL, AGENT_MTLS_PORT" from the boxes' point of view
#   (e.g. a dedicated LoadBalancer in Kubernetes). Advertised verbatim at enrolment.
# AGENT_MTLS_PUBLIC_URL=wss://agents.example.com:8443/agent

# AGENT_MTLS_SANS — extra comma-separated hostnames/IPs baked into the listener's
#   server certificate. Agents pin the deployment CA but still verify the hostname,
#   so list every name a box might dial (localhost, 127.0.0.1, ::1 and the server's
#   os.hostname() are always included).
# AGENT_MTLS_SANS=walls.example.com,10.0.0.7

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Registry store
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# STORE — registry backend: `postgres` (durable, default) or `memory` (test double, no Docker).
# STORE=postgres

# DATABASE_URL — Postgres connection, used when STORE=postgres.
#   Dev default (host processes → Postgres in Docker on localhost):
# DATABASE_URL=postgres://polyptic:polyptic@localhost:5432/polyptic
#   Under the `full` compose profile (server in Docker), reach Postgres at host `db`:
# DATABASE_URL=postgres://polyptic:polyptic@db:5432/polyptic

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Server
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# PORT — the server's HTTP + WS port.
# PORT=8080

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# HTTPS (POL-70 / D88) — the operator surface is HTTPS by default in production
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# PUBLIC_BASE_URL — the ONE public origin of this deployment (scheme://host[:port],
#   no path). Serves two jobs: the last-resort base for request-derived URLs, and —
#   the load-bearing part — the SECURE_COOKIES default: https:// turns the session
#   cookie's Secure flag ON automatically; an explicit http:// turns it OFF (a
#   Secure cookie over plain http is silently dropped by browsers, so login would
#   "succeed" and never persist — POL-43) with a loud plain-HTTP banner at boot.
#   The Helm chart derives this from the ingress host; set it by hand elsewhere.
# PUBLIC_BASE_URL=https://polyptic.example.com

# SECURE_COOKIES — explicit override for the cookie Secure flag; wins over both
#   PUBLIC_BASE_URL's scheme and NODE_ENV=production. Rarely needed: leave unset
#   and set PUBLIC_BASE_URL instead.
# SECURE_COOKIES=true

# TLS_CERT_FILE / TLS_KEY_FILE — serve NATIVE TLS from this process (PEM paths;
#   both together or the server refuses to start). The primary production path is
#   a TLS-terminating ingress/reverse proxy in front of plain :8080 — use native
#   TLS on a bare/docker host with a real certificate. NOTE: this makes EVERY
#   route https, including the netboot depot, which GRUB (no TLS stack, D47)
#   cannot fetch — a netbooting fleet needs the boot paths on plain http.
# TLS_CERT_FILE=/etc/polyptic/tls/fullchain.pem
# TLS_KEY_FILE=/etc/polyptic/tls/privkey.pem

# TLS_MODE — set to `self-signed` for native TLS with NO cert infrastructure at all
#   (the homelab case): the server mints its own CA + server certificate, persists
#   them in the store, and REUSES them on every boot (a re-mint would re-warn every
#   browser). Operators download the CA once from Console ▸ Settings ▸ HTTPS and
#   trust it per device (per-OS instructions live in that card). Conflicts with
#   TLS_CERT_FILE/TLS_KEY_FILE — pick one. The leaf re-mints automatically (same
#   CA, trust survives) when SANs grow or expiry nears.
# TLS_MODE=self-signed

# TLS_SANS — extra comma-separated hostnames/IPs on the self-signed certificate,
#   beyond the automatic set (localhost/loopbacks, this host's name, and the
#   PUBLIC_BASE_URL host). List every name operators dial the console by.
# TLS_SANS=walls.home,10.0.0.7

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Media uploads (Phase 7)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Operators can UPLOAD images/videos (POST /api/v1/media, gated) in addition to
# LINKING external media URLs (Phase 3c). Uploads are streamed to a DISK VOLUME
# (Polyptic deliberately does NOT use S3/MinIO) and served back, ungated, from
# the top-level GET /media/:id (with HTTP Range support so video can seek), so a
# player on another host can fetch them exactly like any external content URL.
#
# MEDIA_DIR — directory where uploaded files are written (<random-id>.<ext>; the
#   client filename is never used for the path). Make sure it is a MOUNTED,
#   PERSISTENT volume in prod so uploads survive restarts/redeploys.
#   Dev default: ./media (relative to the server's working dir).
#   Prod / container: a mounted volume, e.g. /var/lib/polyptic/media.
# MEDIA_DIR=./media

# MEDIA_PUBLIC_BASE — absolute base URL prepended to /media/<id> when an upload
#   becomes a ContentSource.url. MUST be reachable by the wall players + public
#   wall (so in a real deploy this is your server's public HTTPS origin).
#   Falls back to PUBLIC_BASE_URL, then http://localhost:8080.
# MEDIA_PUBLIC_BASE=http://localhost:8080

# MEDIA_MAX_BYTES — maximum accepted upload size, in bytes (streamed to disk;
#   the request is rejected once it exceeds this). Default ~200MB.
# MEDIA_MAX_BYTES=209715200
